  1. How many countries are represented in this dataset? Make a table and a plot that shows the number of countries by continent.

There are a total of 142 countries, including 52 African countries, 33 Asian countries, 30 European countries, 25 American countries, and 2 Oceanian countries

gapminder %>% 
  summarize(dis_con=n_distinct(country)) 
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   dis_con
##     <int>
## 1     142
gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent) %>% 
  summarize(n_con=n_distinct(country)) %>% 
  arrange(-n_con)
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   continent n_con
##   <fct>     <int>
## 1 Africa       52
## 2 Asia         33
## 3 Europe       30
## 4 Americas     25
## 5 Oceania       2
gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent) %>% 
  summarize(n_con=n_distinct(country)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(continent, n_con), y=n_con))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title = "Continent vs Number of Countries",
       x= "Continent",
       y= "Number of Countries")+
  coord_flip()+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust=0.5))

  1. Which country has the largest population growth since 1952? Show this as a table.

China has the largest population growth since 1952

gapminder %>% 
  filter(year>=1952) %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarize(min_pop=min(pop), max_pop=max(pop)) %>% 
  mutate(pop_growth= max_pop-min_pop) %>%

  1. Make a plot that shows population growth for the country you found in question #3. This plot should show the change over time.
gapminder %>% 
  filter(country=="China") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=pop))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(shape=9)+
  labs(title = "Population Change Over Tiime in China Between 1952 and 2007",
       x= "Year",
       y="Population")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))

  1. Make a plot that shows how mean life expectancy has changed over time for each continent. What is your interpretation of what happened in Africa between 1987 and 2002?
gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent, year) %>% 
  summarize(ave_lifex=mean(lifeExp), .groups = "keep") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=ave_lifex, group = continent, color= continent))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(shape=7)+
  labs(title = "Life Expectancy Over Time in Each Continent",
       x="Year",
       y="Mean Life Expectancy")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))

The life expectancy in Africa between 1987 and 2002 barely changed, and I think this is because of the disease outbreak like AIDS, which increases its mortality rate. So, despite having a high birth rate, the high mortality rate keeps the life expectancy rate constant

  1. We are interested in the relationship between per capita GDP and life expectancy; i.e.does having more money help you live longer? Show this as a plot.

The line shows that more money helps you live longer, but the data points itself doesnt show strong correlation between GDP and life expectancy

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=F)+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Money vs. Life Expectancy", 
       x="GDP Per Capita",
       y="Life Expectancy")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Singapore, Norway, Hong Kong, Ireland, Austria

  1. How does per capita GDP growth compare between these same five countries? Show this as a plot.
gapminder %>% 
  filter(country=="Singapore" | country=="Norway" | country=="Hong Kong, China" | country=="Ireland" | country=="Austria") %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=gdpPercap, group = country, color = country))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(shape=5)+
  labs(title = "Per Capita GDP growth vs. Year within Singapore, Norway, Hongkong, Ireland, Austria",
       x="Year",
       y="GDP Per Capita")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))

  1. Do one analysis of your choice that includes a table and plot as outputs.

Make a table and a plot that shows the population change over time in all countries in the Asian continent, and present table with min, max, mean of the population, and the overall population growth, and scale the y axis of the plot to log10 base.

gapminder %>% 
  filter(continent=="Asia") %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarize(min_pop=min(pop), max_pop=max(pop), ave_pop=mean(pop)) %>% 
  mutate(pop_growth=max_pop-min_pop) %>% 
  arrange(-pop_growth)

gapminder %>% 
  filter(continent=="Asia") %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=pop, group = country, color = country))+
  geom_line()+
  scale_y_log10()+
  labs(title = "Year vs. Population in the Asia continent",
       x="Year",
       y="Population")+
  geom_point(shape=9)
